ina]]/Washington Island\n** [[Vostok Island]]\n\n===Marshall Islands===\nIslands of the Republic of the Marshall Islands\n* [[Marshall Islands]]\n** [[Bikini Atoll|Bikini]]\n** [[Enewetak]]\n** [[Kwajalein]]\n** [[Rongelap]]\n** [[Majuro]]\n\n===Mexico===\nIslands of [[Mexico]]:\n* [[Revillagigedo Islands]] \n* [[Rocas Alijos]] \n* [[Guadalupe Island]]\n\n===Micronesia===\nIslands of [[Federated States of Micronesia]]\n* [[Caroline Islands]]\n* [[Pohnpei]]\n* [[Yap]]\n** [[Ulithi]]\n* [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]]\n** [[Puluwat]]\n* [[Kosrae]]\n* [[Guam]]\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[Islands of New Zealand]], including:\n* [[Chatham Islands]]\n** [[Chatham Island]]\n** [[Pitt Island]]\n* [[d'Urville Island (New Zealand)|d'Urville Island]]\n* [[Great Barrier Island]]\n* [[Kapiti Island]]\n* [[Kermadec Islands]]\n** [[Macauley Island]]\n** [[Raoul Island]]\n* [[North Island]]\n* [[South Island]]\n* [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]]\n* [[Waiheke Island]]\n\n===Palau===\nIslands of [[Palau]]:\n* [[Caroline Islands]]\n* [[Ngeruangel]]\n* [[Kayangel]]\n* [[Babeldaob]]\n* [[Ioueldaob]]\n** [[Koror]]\n* [[Peleliu]]\n* [[Angaur]]\n* [[Southwest Islands (Palau)|Southwest Islands]]\n** [[Fanna]]\n** [[Sonsorol]]\n** [[Pulo Anna]]\n** [[Merir]]\n** [[Tobi (island)|Tobi]]\n** [[Helen Reef]]\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\nMain islands of [[Papua New Guinea]] (see [[List of islands of Papua New Guinea]] for more detailed list)\n* [[Papua New Guinea]]\n** [[Bismarck Archipelago]]\n*** [[Admiralty Islands]]\n**** [[Manus Island]]\n*** [[Karkar Island]]\n*** [[New Britain]]\n*** [[New Ireland (island)|New Ireland]]\n*** [[Saint Matthias Group]]\n** [[North Solomon Islands]]\n*** [[Bougainville Island|Bougainville]]\n*** [[Buka Island]]\n** [[Trobriand Islands]]\n*** [[Kiriwina]]\n** [[Woodlark Island]]\n** [[D'Entrecasteaux Islands]]\n***[[Fergusson Island]]\n***[[Goodenough Island]]\n***[[Normanby Island (Papua New Guinea)]]\n** [[Louisiade Archipelago]]\n*** [[Misima Island]]\n*** [[Tagula Island]] or Sudest Island\n*** [[Rossel Island]]\n*** [[Samarai]]\n** [[Daru Island]]\n** [[Kiwai Island]]\n\n===Samoa===\n* [[Samoa]] (western part of the [[Samoa Islands]])\n** [[Savai'i]]\n** [[Upolu]]\n** [[Apolima]]\n** [[Manono Island|Manono]]\n** [[Nuutele]]\n\n===Solomon Islands===\n* [[Solomon Islands]] (see also [[Islands of the Solomon Islands]])\n** [[Rennell and Bellona|Bellona]]\n** [[Choiseul (Solomon Islands)|Choiseul]]\n** [[Florida Island]]\n** [[Guadalcanal]]\n** [[Malaita]]\n** [[Maramasike]]\n** [[New Georgia Islands]]\n** [[Rennell and Bellona|Rennell]]\n** [[Russell Islands]]\n** [[San Cristobal (Solomon Islands)|San Cristobal]]\n** [[Santa Cruz Islands]]\n** [[Santa Isabel Island|Santa Isabel]]\n** [[Shortland Islands]]\n** [[Sikaiana]] (Stewart Islands)\n** [[Tulagi]]\n** [[Ulawa]]\n** [[Uki Island|Uki]]\n\n===Tonga===\n* [[Tonga]] (only main islands or groups, on north-south order. See also complete [[list of islands in Tonga]])\n** [[Niuafo'ou|Niuafoou]]\n** [[Niuatoputapu]] (Keppel's Island)\n** [[Vava'u|Vavau]]\n** [[Kao (island)|Kao]]\n** [[Tofua]]\n** [[Ha'apai|Haapai]]\n** [[Tongatapu]]\n** [['Eua|Eua]]\n\n===Tuvalu===\n[[Tuvalu]]; [[Islands of Tuvalu]]\n* [[Funafuti]] (atoll of at least 30 islands)\n* [[Nanumanga]] (or ''Nanumaga'')\n* [[Nanumea]] (atoll of at least 6 islands)\n* [[Niulakita]]\n* [[Niutao]]\n* [[Nui (atoll)|Nui]] (atoll of at least 21 islands)\n* [[Nukufetau]] (atoll of at least 33 islands)\n* [[Nukulaelae]] (atoll of at least 15 islands)\n* [[Vaitupu]] (atoll of at least 9 islands)\n\n===United States of America===\nPacific islands of [[United States|United States of America]]\n* [[Aleutian Islands]] \n* [[American Samoa]] (Eastern part of the [[Samoa Islands]], United States territory)\n** [[Aunuu]]\n** [[Ofu-Olosega]]\n** [[Rose Atoll]]\n** [[Swains Island]] (Olosenga, Olohega) (Disputed)\n** [[Tau, Samoa|Tau]]\n** [[Tutuila]]\n* [[Channel Islands (California)|Channel Islands of California]]\n* [[Hawaiian Islands]]\n** [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]]\n** [[Kahoolawe]]\n** [[Kauai]]\n** [[Ka'ula]]\n** [[Lanai]]\n** [[Maui]]\n** [[Molokai]]\n** [[Niihau]]\n** [[Oahu]]\n** [[Northwestern Hawaiian Islands]]\n*** [[Kure Atoll|Kure]]\n*** [[Nihoa]]\n*** [[Necker Island (Hawaii)|Necker]]\n*** [[French Frigate Shoals]]\n*** [[Gardner Pinnacles]]\n*** [[Maro Reef]]\n*** [[Laysan]]\n*** [[Lisianski Island|Lisianski]]\n*** [[Pearl and Hermes Reef]]\n* [[Marianas Islands]] \n** [[Guam]]\n** [[Northern Marianas Islands]]\n*** [[Saipan]]\n*** [[Rota (island)|Rota]]\n*** [[Tinian]]\n*** [[Maug]]\n*** [[Pagan Island]]\n*** [[Alamagan]]\n*** [[Farallon de Pajaros]]\n* [[United States Minor Outlying Islands]]\n** [[Baker Island]] \n** [[Howland Island]]\n** [[Jarvis Island]]\n** [[Johnston Atoll]] \n** [[Kingman Reef]] \n** [[Midway Atoll|Midway]]\n** [[Palmyra Atoll|Palmyra]]\n** [[Wake Island]]\n\n===Vanuatu===\n(For a complete list see [[List of islands of Vanuatu]])\n\n(Approximately from north to south)\n* [[Torres Islands]]\n* [[Banks Islands]]\n** [[Gaua]] (Santa Maria Island) \n** [[Vanua Lava]]\n* [[Espiritu Santo]]\n* [[Malo Island|Malo]]\n* [[Pentecost Island]]\n* [[Ambae]] (Aoba)\n* [[Maewo]]\n* [[Malakula]]\n* [[Ambrym]]\n* [[Paama]]\n* [[Epi (island)|Epi]]\n* [[Shepherd Islands]]\n** [[Tongoa]] ([[Kuwae|Kuwa\u00e9]])\n* [[Efate]], the Island of the national capital [[Port Vila]]\n* [[Lelepa (island)|Lelepa]]\n* [[Tanna (island)|Tanna]]\n* [[Futuna Island, Vanuatu|Futuna]]\n* [[Erromango]]\n* [[Aneityum]]\n\n==Other islands==\n* [[Japan]] (the [[Japanese Archipelago]] of 6,852 islands)\n* [[Marcus Island]] (Japan)\n* [[Kuril Islands]] (Russia)\n* [[Line Islands]]\n* [[Lord Howe Island]] (Australia)\n* [[Norfolk Island]] (Australia)\n* [[Nauru]]\n* [[Niue]] (Savage Island)\n* [[Okinotori Islands]] (Japan)\n* [[Philippines]]\n** [[Miangas]]\n** [[Spratly Islands]]\n** [[Island of Palmas]]\n** [[Scarborough Shoal]]\n* [[Pitcairn Islands]] (UK)\n** [[Henderson Island (Pitcairn Islands)|Henderson Island]]\n** [[Oeno Island]]\n** [[Ducie Island]]\n* [[Sakhalin]] (Russia)\n* [[Taiwan]]\n* [[Tokelau]] \n** [[Atafu]] (Duke of York Island)\n** [[Fakaofo]] (Bowditch Island)\n** [[Nukunonu]] (Duke of Clarence Island)\n** [[Swains Island|Olohega]] (Swains island) (disputed)\n* [[Torres Strait Islands]] (Australia)\n* [[Hunter Island (South Pacific)|Hunter]] (claimed by France and Vanuatu)\n* [[Matthew Island|Matthew]] (claimed by France and Vanuatu)\n* [[Wallis and Futuna]] (France)\n** [[Alofi Island|Alofi]]\n** [[Futuna Island, Wallis and Futuna|Futuna]]\n** [[Wallis Island|Wallis (Uvea)]]\n* [[Willis Island]] (Australia)\n* [[Auckland Islands]]\n\nNorth Pacific Islands:\n* [[Nunivak Island]]\n* [[St. Lawrence Island]]\n* [[Alexander Archipelago]]\n\nEastern Pacific Islands:\n* [[Cocos Island]]\n* [[Chilo\u00e9 Island]]\n* [[Pearl Islands]]\n* [[Pun\u00e1 Island]]\n* [[Gorgona Island, Colombia]]\n* [[Malpelo Island]]\n* [[Tibur\u00f3n Island]]\n* [[Archangel Island]]\n* [[Cedros Island]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Antarctic and subantarctic islands]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|}}\n\n{{Countries and territories of Oceania}}\n{{Regions of Oceania}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Pacific Ocean| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of islands by ocean|Pacific]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "CityOfSails2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNew Zealand:change section to summary style)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_islands_in_the_Pacific_Ocean"}
{"title_page": "Association of Classical and Christian Schools", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Association of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2010}}\nThe '''Association of Classical Christian Schools''' ('''ACCS''') is an organization founded in 1994 to encourage the formation of [[Christian schools]] using a model of [[classical education movement|classical education]].  The association's website lists over 300 member schools with more than 40,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classicalchristian.org/media-kit/|title=Press & Media Kit|website=Association of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\nThe [[classical Christian education]] movement was launched by the publication in 1991 of a book entitled ''[https://www.crossway.org/books/recovering-the-lost-tools-of-learning-tpb/ Recovering the Lost Tools of Learning]'' by [[Douglas Wilson (theologian)|Doug Wilson]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Wilson | first = Doug | title = Recovering the Lost Tools of Learning | publisher = Crossway Books | location = Wheaton | year = 1991 | isbn = 0-89107-583-6 | url = https://archive.org/details/recoveringlostto00wils }}</ref> Wilson was also the founder of one of the first classical Christian schools in [[Moscow, Idaho]], [http://www.logosschool.com Logos School].  \n\nWilson himself had drawn inspiration from an earlier article published by [[Dorothy Sayers]] entitled \"[https://classicalchristian.org/the-lost-tools-of-learning-dorothy-sayers/?v=a44707111a05 The Lost Tools of Learning]\" (1948).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sayers|first=Dorothy Leigh|title=The Lost Tools of Learning: Symposium on Education|publisher=CrossReach Publications|year=2016|isbn=1520144776|location=Edinburgh, Scottland|pages=}}</ref> Sayers was a colleague of C.S. Lewis and [[J. R. R. Tolkien]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inklingbooks.com/aboutinkling/inklingsofoxford/inklingsofoxford.html|title=Inklings of Oxford|website=www.inklingbooks.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In this article she derided modern education methods and called for a return to the ancient classical [[Trivium (education)|trivium]].\n\nThe classical Christian education movement has also been influenced by ''Norms and Nobility'' by [[David V. Hicks]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Hicks|first=David|url=https://archive.org/details/normsnobilitytre00davi|title=Norms and Nobility|publisher=University Press of America|year=1999|isbn=0-7618-1467-1|location=Washington}}</ref> as well as the [http://circeinstitute.org CiRCE Institute], founded by Andrew Kern, which exists to promote classical Christian education.  In 2016, Kevin Clark and Ravi Jain authored ''The Liberal Arts Tradition'', published by Classical Academic Press which was later revised in 2019, with a forward by [[Peter Kreeft|Dr. Peter Kreeft]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Clark, Kevin (Kevin Wayne),|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864848683|title=The liberal arts tradition : a philosophy of Christian classical education|others=Jain, Ravi Scott., Kreeft, Peter.,|isbn=978-1-60051-225-4|edition=Verson 1|location=Camp Hill, PA|oclc=864848683}}</ref>  This work was widely endorsed as an essential explanation of the philosophy of classical Christian education by over 14 leaders within the movement, including [[John Frame (theologian)|Dr. John Frame]], Andrew Kern, [https://www.baylor.edu/greattexts/index.php?id=960241 Dr. Phillip J. Donnelly] (Baylor Honors College), and David Goodwin, President of the ACCS.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ACCS conducts [https://repairingtheruins.org Repairing the Ruins], an annual conference in June that draws between 1000 and 1300 classical educators annually.  The conference took its name from an essay [[Of Education|\"Of Education\"]] by John Milton.<ref>Milton, John. \"Of Education.\" ''Milton on Education: The Tractate of Education with Supplementary Extracts from Other Writings of Milton''. Ed. Morley Oliver Ainsworth. New Haven: Yale UP, 1928. 51\u201364.</ref>  The public information service of the ACCS is [https://classicaldifference.com The Classical Difference.]  This service operates online and in print.  The Classical Difference magazine has a circulation of more than 16,000 parents and educators quarterly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classicaldifference.com/about-the-classical-difference/|title=About \"The Classical Difference\" - Christian Schools|website=The Classical Difference|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>  \n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.classicalchristian.org Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Association Of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)}}\n\n{{Association of Classical and Christian Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Christian educational organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Classical Christian schools]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Private and independent school organizations]]\n[[Category:United States schools associations]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Association of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2010}}\nThe '''Association of Classical and Christian Schools''' ('''ACCS''') is an organization founded in 1994 to encourage the formation of [[Christian schools]] using a model of [[classical education movement|classical education]].  The association's website lists over 300 member schools with more than 40,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classicalchristian.org/media-kit/|title=Press & Media Kit|website=Association of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\nThe [[classical Christian education]] movement was launched by the publication in 1991 of a book entitled ''[https://www.crossway.org/books/recovering-the-lost-tools-of-learning-tpb/ Recovering the Lost Tools of Learning]'' by [[Douglas Wilson (theologian)|Doug Wilson]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Wilson | first = Doug | title = Recovering the Lost Tools of Learning | publisher = Crossway Books | location = Wheaton | year = 1991 | isbn = 0-89107-583-6 | url = https://archive.org/details/recoveringlostto00wils }}</ref> Wilson was also the founder of one of the first classical Christian schools in [[Moscow, Idaho]], [http://www.logosschool.com Logos School].  \n\nWilson himself had drawn inspiration from an earlier article published by [[Dorothy Sayers]] entitled \"[https://classicalchristian.org/the-lost-tools-of-learning-dorothy-sayers/?v=a44707111a05 The Lost Tools of Learning]\" (1948).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sayers|first=Dorothy Leigh|title=The Lost Tools of Learning: Symposium on Education|publisher=CrossReach Publications|year=2016|isbn=1520144776|location=Edinburgh, Scottland|pages=}}</ref> Sayers was a colleague of C.S. Lewis and [[J. R. R. Tolkien]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inklingbooks.com/aboutinkling/inklingsofoxford/inklingsofoxford.html|title=Inklings of Oxford|website=www.inklingbooks.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In this article she derided modern education methods and called for a return to the ancient classical [[Trivium (education)|trivium]].\n\nThe classical Christian education movement has also been influenced by ''Norms and Nobility'' by [[David V. Hicks]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Hicks|first=David|url=https://archive.org/details/normsnobilitytre00davi|title=Norms and Nobility|publisher=University Press of America|year=1999|isbn=0-7618-1467-1|location=Washington}}</ref> as well as the [http://circeinstitute.org CiRCE Institute], founded by Andrew Kern, which exists to promote classical Christian education.  In 2016, Kevin Clark and Ravi Jain authored ''The Liberal Arts Tradition'', published by Classical Academic Press which was later revised in 2019, with a forward by [[Peter Kreeft|Dr. Peter Kreeft]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Clark, Kevin (Kevin Wayne),|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864848683|title=The liberal arts tradition : a philosophy of Christian classical education|others=Jain, Ravi Scott., Kreeft, Peter.,|isbn=978-1-60051-225-4|edition=Verson 1|location=Camp Hill, PA|oclc=864848683}}</ref>  This work was widely endorsed as an essential explanation of the philosophy of classical Christian education by over 14 leaders within the movement, including [[John Frame (theologian)|Dr. John Frame]], Andrew Kern, [https://www.baylor.edu/greattexts/index.php?id=960241 Dr. Phillip J. Donnelly] (Baylor Honors College), and David Goodwin, President of the ACCS.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe ACCS conducts [https://repairingtheruins.org Repairing the Ruins], an annual conference in June that draws between 1000 and 1300 classical educators annually.  The conference took its name from an essay [[Of Education|\"Of Education\"]] by John Milton.<ref>Milton, John. \"Of Education.\" ''Milton on Education: The Tractate of Education with Supplementary Extracts from Other Writings of Milton''. Ed. Morley Oliver Ainsworth. New Haven: Yale UP, 1928. 51\u201364.</ref>  The public information service of the ACCS is [https://classicaldifference.com The Classical Difference.]  This service operates online and in print.  The Classical Difference magazine has a circulation of more than 16,000 parents and educators quarterly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classicaldifference.com/about-the-classical-difference/|title=About \"The Classical Difference\" - Christian Schools|website=The Classical Difference|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>  \n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.classicalchristian.org Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Association Of Classical Christian Schools (ACCS)}}\n\n{{Association of Classical and Christian Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Christian educational organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Classical Christian schools]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Private and independent school organizations]]\n[[Category:United States schools associations]]\n", "name_user": "DCGoodwin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected name to remove and in text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_of_Classical_and_Christian_Schools"}
{"title_page": "Citadel LLC", "text_new": "{{UDP|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Citadel LLC\n| logo                = Citadel LLC Logo.svg\n| logo_size           = 220px\n| logo_alt            = \n| type                = [[Limited Liability Company|LLC]]\n| industry            = [[Hedge fund]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|1990}} in [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| predecessor         = {{unbulleted list|\u2022 1994-?: Citadel Investment Group, LLC|\u2022 1990<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2017February3MarekLynne\" />-1994: Wellington Financial}}\n| founder             = [[Kenneth C. Griffin]]<br/><small> (Founder & CEO)</small>\n| location            = [[Citadel Center]]<br />[[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| key_people          = [[Peng Zhao (businessman)|Peng Zhao]]<br/><small> (CEO of Citadel Securities)</small>\n| num_employees       = 1,400\n| products            = {{unbulleted list|[[Alternative investments]]| [[Market maker|Market making]]}}\n| revenue             = \n| subsid              = \n| homepage            = {{URL|https://www.citadel.com/}}\n| aum                 = [[US$]]32.0 billion (2019)<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2019August1FletcherLaurence\">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Laurence|title=Citadel adds traders to profit from central bank stimulus shifts|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1c5272d4-b446-11e9-8cb2-799a3a8cf37b|accessdate=13 December 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=1 August 2019|location=London|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0884-6782}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Citadel LLC''' (formerly known as '''Citadel Investment Group, LLC''') is an American global financial institution. Founded in 1990 by [[Kenneth C. Griffin|Kenneth Griffin]], the company operates two primary businesses: Citadel, one of the world's largest alternative asset managers with more than [[US$]]32 billion in assets under management; and Citadel Securities, one of the leading [[market maker]]s in the world, whose trading products include [[Stock|equities]], [[Option (finance)|equity options]], and interest rate swaps for retail and institutional clients.\n\nThe company has more than 1,400 employees, with headquarters in [[Chicago]], and offices throughout [[North America]], [[Asia]] and [[Europe]].\n\n== History ==\nKen Griffin started his trading career out of his dorm room at [[Harvard University]] in 1987 trading convertible-bonds.<ref name=\"WSJ2008November7StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|last2=Zuckerman|first2=Gregory|title=Hedge Fund Selling Puts New Stress on Market|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122602205734807307|accessdate=11 March 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=7 November 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> As a sophomore, he traded convertible bonds and hooked a satellite dish to the roof of his dormitory.<ref name=\"ChicagoMagazine2011June8MeyerGraham\">{{cite news|last1=Meyer|first1=Graham|title=The File on Citadel\u2019s Ken Griffin|url=https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/June-2011/The-File-on-Citadels-Ken-Griffin/|accessdate=11 March 2015|agency=Chicago Tribune Media|issue=Politics & City Life|publisher=Chicago Magazine|date=8 June 2011|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|issn=0362-4595}}</ref> After graduating with a degree in economics, Griffin joined Chicago-based hedge fund Glenwood Partners. According to a ''New York Times'' report, Citadel was started with $4.6 million in capital.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|title=Citadel Chief Gives Up Dream for Investment Bank|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/08/11/citadel-chief-gives-up-dream-for-investment-bank/|accessdate=25 February 2015|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=11 August 2011|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> Citadel was originally named Wellington Financial Group after its flagship fund. The company name was changed to Citadel in 1994. Within eight years, the firm had more than $2 billion in assets.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\">{{cite news|last1=Lux|first1=Hal|title=Boy Wonder|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b15134ls4fblx7/boy-wonder|accessdate=24 July 2015|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=31 August 2001|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=0020-3580}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Citadel started requiring investors to accept terms that \"significantly restrict[ed] their ability to withdraw their capital\", according to ''Institutional Investor''.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\" /> When fund Long-Term Capital Management collapsed later that year, Citadel's capital lockdown made it \"a rare buyer, as desperate hedge funds unloaded bond inventory\".<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\" /> In 2006, Citadel and [[JP Morgan Chase]] took over the energy portfolio and division of failed hedge fund [[Amaranth Advisors]], which had suffered a 65% ($6 billion) loss in assets.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006November26\" /> On November 2006 Citadel issued $2 billion of investment grade bonds to enable access to borrow money at a lower rate than it would otherwise be able to.<ref name=\"WSJ2006November30CoxRob\">{{cite news|last1=Cox|first1=Rob|last2=Christy|first2=John|title=Hedge Fund Citadel Finds a Way To Keep Financial Independence|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116485503536736551|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=BreakingViews|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=30 November 2006|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n[[File:The Citadel Center, Chicago Loop, Chicago, Illinois (11004378483).jpg|thumb|The entrance to Citadel's Chicago headquarters, 2009.]]\nIn October 2008, S&P lowered the outlook for Citadel's Kensington and Wellington Funds from 'stable' to 'negative', citing a 'heightened risk of significant redemptions, challenging performance prospects due to highly volatile capital markets and a very difficult funding environment'.<ref name=\"MarketWatch2008November18BarrAlistair\">{{cite news|last1=Barr|first1=Alistair|title=S&P downgrades debt of Citadel's main fund|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/sp-downgrades-debt-of-citadels-main-fund-after-losses|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Hedge Funds|publisher=MarketWatch|date=18 November 2008|location=San Francisco, United States|language=English}}</ref> In October 2006 following ongoing market concerns over the performance and liquidity of Citadel and the widening of Citadel credit default swaps from 12% upfront on Sep 30, 2008 to 30% upfront on Oct 23, 2008 Citadel held a conference call on Oct 24th 2008 with its noteholders stating that performance to date was -35% for Kensington and Wellington and that the fund maintained a liquid cash position in excess of 30% of capital and had undrawn capacity of $8bn in its tri-party credit lines.<ref name=\"WSJ2018October25StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|last2=Hilsenrath|first2=Jon|title=Citadel Seeks to Reassure Debt Holders|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122488910091368491|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=25 October 2018|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Based on the 2006 SEC filing at the time of its bond offering, the company's leverage ratio was in excess of 7.8 to 1, although some reports suggest this has been reduced to 4 to 1 presently.  This implies a ratio of at least 7.5% of cash to assets.\n\nIn November and again in December 2008 Standard & Poor's Ratings Services lowered its long-term and short-term counterparty credit ratings on Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd. and Citadel Wellington LLC \"to just a notch above junk and then withdrew the ratings at the company's request.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2008December18MillerJay\">{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Jay|title=S&P Cuts, Pulls Counterparty Ratings|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122964818306320429|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=18 December 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In March of 2008, prior to the collapse of Bear Sterns, Citadel was named as a potential bidder for the business. However, Kate Kelly, a Wall Street Journal writer, claims the parties never met to discuss a potential acquisition by Citadel as senior Bear employees believed that Citadel was shorting the company <ref> Kate Kelly, 'Street Fighters: the last 72 hours of Bear Sterns, the Toughest Firm on Wall Street' (London, Penguin Books, 2010) 96 </ref> In February 2009 under pressure from banks Citadel Investment Group sold \"some securities and reduce its borrowing to finance trades.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2009February17PulliamSusan\">{{cite news|last1=Pulliam|first1=Susan|last2=Strasburg|first2=Jenny|title=Brokerages Tighten Hedge Fund Financing|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123483417670296081|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=17 February 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In 2015 the Wall Street Journal described Citadel's position in 2008 as existing \"at the brink of collapse during the financial crisis, amid heavy losses and a struggle to build an investment bank.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" /> During the 2008 financial crisis, the firm's Kensington and Wellington Funds lost 55 percent of their value by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-05-17/citadel-said-to-make-withdrawals-easier-for-hedge-fund-clients | title=Citadel Said to Ease Withdrawal Rules for Hedge-Fund Clients | publisher=Bloomberg | date=17 May 2011 | accessdate=24 July 2015 | author=Burton, Katherine}}</ref> Griffin said, \"we were losing hundreds of millions of dollars a week, if not more,\" and further said \"CNBC parked a van in front of Citadel waiting to break the story of our demise. \u2026 We sold assets. We closed business lines. We let people go. We suspended redemptions. Our management team absorbed $500 million in costs on behalf of our investors...\"<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune2013May22HarrisMelissa\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Melissa|title=Citadel's Kenneth Griffin exposes 'cronyism,' causes a stir at Economic Club|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2013-05-22-ct-biz-0522-confidential-griffin-20130522-story.html|accessdate=24 July 2015|agency=Tribune Publishing Company|issue=Business|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=22 May 2013|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=2165-171X}}</ref>\n\nCitadel suspended shareholder redemptions, which Griffin called one of the \"most difficult decisions\" in Citadel history.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|title=Citadel Clears Its High Water Mark|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/01/20/citadel-clears-its-high-water-mark/|accessdate=13 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=20 January 2012|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> Griffin later conceded that the firm was \"overly confident\" it could \"weather any financial storm\". He covered all investor management expenses during that period.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Citadel\u2019s primary sources of revenue come from charging clients performance fees on their two largest funds: Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\">{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Gregory|last2=Checkler|first2=Joseph|title=Citadel Opens Its 'Gates' on Better Results|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125684219883316671|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=EUROPE|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=30 October 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Because the assets in those funds decreased by 50 percent, Citadel was unable to charge performance fees until it could make up the 50 percent lost; the company would have to make a 100 percent investment return before it could see any more revenue and begin charging clients again.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\">{{cite news|last1=Marek|first1=Lynne|title=Citadel gets slow start in i-banking|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20101106/ISSUE01/311069967/citadel-gets-slow-start-in-i-banking|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=6 November 2010|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> To resolve this issue, Griffin announced that Citadel would incorporate greater portfolio diversification and take up investment strategies that were easier to get out of quickly and also continue efforts to diversify beyond hedge funds, with computer-driven, high-frequency trading.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" /> In 2009, Griffin expanded the scope of business lines at Citadel Securities, a market maker firm founded in 2001, to establish [[investment banking]] and associated financial security sales and trading capabilities.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" />\n\nOn January 17, 2012, Citadel's flagship funds, Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC, crossed their respective high water marks, earning back the 50 percent of assets lost during the 2008 financial crisis.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Having made up the losses, Citadel could once again charge client fees for managing their money and take a percentage of profits.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Citadel under Griffin's leadership was reported as differentiating from hedge funds rivals post 2008 financial crisis with an \"aggressive expansion.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" /> Starting at the beginning of 2014, over an 18 months period the hedge fund's assets under management increased $10 billion; from $16 billion to $26 billion as a result of \"a 29% rise for its main hedge funds and a flow of new cash.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\">{{cite news|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|title=Citadel's Ken Griffin Leaves 2008 Tumble Far Behind|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/citadels-ken-griffin-leaves-2008-tumble-far-behind-1438655887|accessdate=23 October 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=3 August 2015|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In January 2020, Citadel Securities paid $97m in China trading settlement, after Chinese regulator ends longstanding investigation into Citadel and other local groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.financemagnates.com/institutional-forex/regulation/citadel-securities-fined-97m-in-china-for-malicious-short-selling/|title=Citadel Securities Pays $97m to Settle with China Regulators}}</ref>\n\n== Citadel & group of companies ==\nThere are three companies Citadel the asset manager, Citadel Securities a market maker and Citadel Technology. \n\n=== Citadel ===\nAs of January 2016, Citadel manages more than $29 billion in capital and is one of the world's largest asset managers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://upstart.bizjournals.com/executives/features/2007/04/16/opening-up-the-citadel.html?page=all | title=Opening Up the Citadel | publisher=Upstart Business Journal | date=16 April 2007 | accessdate=24 February 2015 | author=Kolhatkar, Sheelah}}</ref> Citadel ranks as the eleventh largest hedge fund manager in the world,<ref name=\"Rose-Smith, Imogen 2006 p. 3\">Rose-Smith, Imogen (2006 2006). \"Land of the Giants\" (PDF). Alpha magazine. p. 3. Retrieved 2008-03-20 (dead link).</ref> and in 2006 the second largest multi-strategy hedge fund globally.<ref name=\"fnFinancialNews2006December4HutchingsWilliam\">{{cite news|last1=Hutchings|first1=William|title=Citadel leads the way in financial self-sufficiency|url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/citadel-leads-the-way-in-financial-self-sufficiency-20061204|accessdate=27 January 2007|agency=FINANCIAL NEWS|publisher=fn Financial News|date=4 December 2006|language=English}}</ref> Citadel's group of hedge funds rank among the largest and most successful hedge funds in the world.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2014/07/15/two-new-members-elected-university-chicago-board-trustees | title=Two new members elected to University of Chicago Board of Trustees | publisher=U Chicago News | date=15 July 2014 | accessdate=24 February 2015 | author1=Allen, Susie|author2 = Huang, Wen}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Citadel became the first foreign hedge fund to complete a yuan fundraising as part of a program to allow Chinese investors to invest in overseas hedge funds.<ref name=\"barrons\">{{cite news|url=http://online.barrons.com/articles/SB51367578116875004693704580480163105061670|title=Exclusive: Who Makes Money on Your Stock Trades|author=Bill Alpert|date=February 28, 2015|newspaper=Barron's|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Investment strategies ====\nCitadel manages funds across five different investment strategies including equities, commodities, fixed income, quantitative strategies, and credit.<ref name = dealbooknytimes>{{Cite web | url = https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/01/10/citadel-posted-25-return-last-year-beating-industry-again/?_r=1 | title = Citadel Posted 25% Return Last Year, Beating Industry Again | publisher = DealBook | date = January 10, 2013 | accessdate = July 27, 2015 | author = Michael J. De La Merced}}</ref>\n\n'''Commodities''' - Energy trading: Griffin began recruiting the energy traders from Enron the day after it collapsed for a new business including \"a team of traders, meteorologists and researchers\" building what in 2011 was amongst the industries biggest energy trading groups<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\" />\n\n'''Reinsurance''' - Citadel wanted to allocate the investment capital with its two funds, Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC, to investments that the company thought to be uncorrelated to their other investment strategies.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\">{{cite news|last1=Zuill|first1=Lilla|last2=Orr|first2=Bernard|title=Hedge fund Citadel shuttering Bermuda reinsurer|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-citadel-reinsurer/exclusive-hedge-fund-citadel-shuttering-bermuda-reinsurer-idUSTRE4A70G420081108|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=7 November 2008|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref> To achieve this move, Citadel, through capitalization via their funds, entered the reinsurer industry, which provides insurance companies with their own policies to spread the risk of losses that they have given to their customers, in 2004 by founding CIG Reinsurance Ltd (CIG Re), a Bermuda-based catastrophe reinsurer providing $450 million in capital.<ref name=\"WSJ2005July27AnandShefali\">{{cite news|last1=Anand|first1=Shefali|title=Looking Afield, Hedge Funds Launch Reinsurance Firms|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112242824590496964|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=27 July 2005|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Citadel additionally founded $500 million reinsurer New Castle Re in 2005, seeking to capitalize on rising prices for reinsurance in the wake of [[Hurricane Katrina|Hurricane Katrina\u2019s]] damage to property coverage costs.<ref name=\"MarketWatch2005November4BarrAlistair\">{{cite news|last1=Barr|first1=Alistair|title=Citadel forms new reinsurer - New Castle Re targets catastrophe reinsurance, AM Best says|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/citadel-forms-new-reinsurer-new-castle-re-am-best-says|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=MarketWatch|date=4 November 2005|location=San Francisco, United States|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006August18AndersonaugJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Andersonaug|first1=Jenny|title=Hedge Funds Place Big Bets on Hurricane Season|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/18/business/18insider.html|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business Day - Insider|page=C7|publisher=New York Times|date=18 August 2006|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> In 2006, Citadel\u2019s two funds had approximately 10 percent of its assets invested in reinsurance.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2006December8PittmanMark\">{{cite news|last1=Pittman|first1=Mark|title=Citadel sells bonds|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20061208/BUSINESS/312089909|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Bloomberg|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=8 December 2006|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\nCitadel wound down CIG Re in November of 2008 because the company could not achieve a financial strength rating, and as a result could not compete in comparison to other companies in the industry.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> Meanwhile, New Castle Re remained open and received an 'A-' rating from [[AM Best]] in November of 2008.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> However, a month later on December 17, 2008, AM Best announced that New Castle Re\u2019s rating was under review when Citadel\u2019s funds experienced increased redemption requests as a result of the financial crisis.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2008December17KentJonathan\">{{cite news|last1=Kent|first1=Jonathan|title=Citadel's hedge fund woes threaten New Castle Re's rating|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20081217/BUSINESS/312179954|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=17 December 2008|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref> Two days later on December 19, it was reported that Citadel would not be renewing the rights in New Castle Re contracts, but that Torus Insurance Holdings in Bermuda would do so.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2008December19\">{{cite news|title=Torus takes New Castle Re renewal rights|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20081219/BUSINESS/312199894|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=19 December 2008|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref> In January of 2009, Citadel placed New Castle Re into run-off.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2009July15\">{{cite news|title=Chris McKeown, the founder of Bermuda reinsurers CIG Reinsurance Ltd. and New Castle Reinsurance Co., has been named chief executive officer of global analytical and specialty practices.|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20090715/BUSINESS/307159960|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=15 July 2009|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref>\n\n'''Risk management - '''The firm's risk management philosophy is focused on three main areas: risk capital allocation, stress exposure and liquidity management.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\">{{citeweb|title=Are You Prepared for the Next Crash?|author=Amanda Cantrell|publisher=Institutional Investor's Alpha|date=10 December 2015|url=http://www.institutionalinvestorsalpha.com/Article/3513063/Are-Hedge-Funds-Prepared-for-the-Next-Crash.html}}</ref> Citadel's risk management center has 36 monitors displaying more than 50,000 instruments being traded within the firm's portfolios.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\"/> The firm runs 500 stress tests each day to simulate the impact of potential economic and geopolitical crises or other market dislocation.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\"/> Citadel aggregates investment positions on trading screens to calculate \"more than 500 doomsday scenarios\" to assess the potential of risk for the firm.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\nIn 2014, Citadel rated an A grade for risk management in the annual Institutional Investor Hedge Fund Report Card.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2014June27HurstGeorgina\">{{cite news|last1=Hurst|first1=Georgina|title=A Winning Night for Hedge Fund Managers and Investors|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b14zbj8sby92mq/a-winning-night-for-hedge-fund-managers-and-investors|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|issue=Corner Office|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=27 June 2014|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=0020-3580}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2015, [[Ben S. Bernanke]], who was the United States [[Federal Reserve]] chairman for eight years, joined Citadel as a senior adviser on global economic and financial issues.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015April16SorkinAndrewRoss\">{{cite news|last1=Sorkin|first1=AndrewRoss|last2=Stevenson|first2=Alexandra|title=Ben Bernanke Will Work With Citadel, a Hedge Fund, as an Adviser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/16/business/ben-bernanke-will-work-with-citadel-a-hedge-fund-as-an-adviser.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|page=B1|publisher=New York Times|date=16 April 2015|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> In January 2017, Joanna Welsh became the Chief Risk Officer.\n\n=== Citadel Securities ===\n==== Market Maker ====\nCitadel Securities was formed in 2001, and is a market maker, providing liquidity and trade execution to retail and institutional clients.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" /> Citadel Securities automation has resulted in more reliable trading at lower costs and with tighter spreads.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2012October13MarekLynne\">{{cite news|last1=Marek|first1=Lynne|title=Citadel's big move into the markets|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20121013/ISSUE01/310139980/citadel-becomes-top-broker-on-nasdaq|accessdate=11 December 2014|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=13 October 2012|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> Barron's recently ranked Citadel Securities #1 in providing price improvement for investors in both S&P 500 and non-S&P shares.<ref name = barrons/>\n\nIn 2009 Citadel Investment Group and the Chicago Mercantile Exchanged partnered to create a credit-default swaps electronic-trading platform.<ref name=\"WSJ2009May14LynchSarah\">{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=Sarah|last2=Ng|first2=Serena|title=U.S. Moves to Regulate Derivatives Trade|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124224226775916215|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=14 May 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nCitadel Securities is the largest market maker in options in the U.S., executing about 25 percent U.S.-listed equity options volume.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Citadel wants to shape the rules of the game|author=Lynne Marek|magazine=Crain's Chicago Business|date=5 December 2015|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151205/ISSUE01/312059991/citadel-wants-to-shape-the-rules-of-the-game}}</ref> According to the ''Wall Street Journal'', about one-third of stock orders from individual investors is completed through Citadel, which accounts for about 10% of the firm's revenue.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\nCitadel Securities also executes about 13 percent of U.S. consolidated volume in equities and 28 percent of U.S. retail equities volume.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-04-11/citadel-fund-said-to-quadruple-with-high-frequency-trades.html | title=Citadel Fund Said to Quadruple With High-Frequency Trades | publisher=Bloomberg Business | date=10 April 2014 | accessdate=26 February 2015 | author=Burton, Katherine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Citadel Securities expanded its market-making offering to interest-rate swaps, one of the most commonly-traded derivatives.<ref name=\"WSJ2014June6AlbaneseChiara\">{{cite news|last1=Albanese|first1=Chiara|title=Citadel to Offer Trading in Interest-Rate Swaps|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/citadel-to-offer-trading-in-interest-rate-swaps-1402070439|accessdate=27 July 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=6 June 2014|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> \n\nBy 2015 Citadel Securities had become the world\u2019s largest interest-rate-swap trader by number of transactions replacing Wall Street banks.<ref name=\"WSJ2015December2ZuckermanGregory\">{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Gregory|last2=Cherney|first2=Mike|title=Wall Street Goes Short on Bond Traders|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-goes-short-on-bond-traders-1449102232|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=MARKETS|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=2 December 2015|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n==== Investment bank ====\nIn 2008 Citadel Securities hired 70 people and Rohit D'Souza, a banker from Merrill Lynch, who left after eight months \"to build an investment bank\" and brokerage.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /> By August 2011, Citadel ended its foray into investment banking to instead focus on electronic trading and market making.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/974e99a6-c465-11e0-ad9a-00144feabdc0|title=Citadel abandons plan to rival banks|last=McCrum|first=Dan|date=August 11, 2011|work=Financial Times|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Citadel Technology ===\nCitadel Technology, established in 2009, is the wholly owned and independently operated affiliate of Citadel.<ref name = wallstreettech>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.wallstreetandtech.com/asset-management/redi-and-citadel-technology-tackle-the--holy-grail-/d/d-id/1268435? | title=REDI and Citadel Technology Tackle the \"Holy Grail\" | magazine=InformationWeek | date=25 September 2013 | accessdate=26 February 2015 | author=Schmerken, Ivy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://marketsmedia.com/citadel-carves-out-technology-niche/ | title=Citadel Carves Out Technology Niche | publisher=Markets Media | date=20 April 2013 | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref> It offers investment management technology, developed internally at Citadel, to a wide range of firms and funds.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.waterstechnology.com/buy-side-technology/analysis/2255916/citadel-technology-preps-endtoend-solutions-suite | title=Citadel technology preps end to end solutions suite | publisher=Waters Technology | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Citadel Technology announced a partnership with [[REDI Global Technologies|REDI]]. The partnership combines Citadel's order management system (OMS) with REDI's execution management capabilities (EMS).<ref name = wallstreettech/>\n\n=== Sold and closed companies ===\nCitadel Solutions - Citadel's fund-administration arm.<ref name=\"WSJ2009March6StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|title=Lower Fees on Citadel's New Fund|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123630573986048063|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=6 March 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n\n=== Citadel Ownership ===\n\nIn November 2006, Citadel became the second [[hedge fund]] to publicly issue debt [[bond (finance)|bonds]] to investors in the form of senior unsecured debt totaling $2 billion, in an arrangement managed by [[Lehman Brothers]] and [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006November26\">{{cite news|title=Citadel Planning $2 Billion Debt Offering|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2006/11/28/citadel-to-plan-2-billion-debt-offering/|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=26 November 2006|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref>\n\n=== Employees ===\nThe fund has become known for having one of the largest personnel turnovers in Chicago gaining the nickname of \"Chicago's revolving door\"<ref name=\"Fortune2007April3VickersMarcia\">{{cite news|last1=Vickers|first1=Marcia|title=A hedge fund superstar - Citadel founder Ken Griffin is already one of the world's most powerful investors.|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/04/16/8404298/index.htm|accessdate=26 April 2008|agency=Fortune Media IP Limited|publisher=Fortune|date=3 April 2007|location=United States|language=English}}</ref> and the New York Times reported \"the firm is unique in its reputation for being a revolving door.\"<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\" /><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010December27AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|title=Citadel Founder Offers Thanks and Apologies on Anniversary|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/27/citadel-founder-offers-thanks-apology-on-anniversary|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=27 December 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> It is also reported that turnover is aligned with the hedge fund industry.<ref name=\"Fortune2007April3VickersMarcia\" />\n\nIn March 2015, Citadel received a Top 10 Great Workplaces in Financial Services ranking by the Great Places to Work Institute, based on a survey by Citadel employees.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2015March6KaposShia\">{{cite news|last1=Kapos|first1=Shia|title=Why Ken Griffin hated one of his first jobs|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20150306/ISSUE09/150309873/ceo-ken-griffin-discusses-citadel-being-honored-as-a-great-place-to-work|accessdate=29 April 2015|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=6 March 2015|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref>\n\n=== Market advocacy ===\nCitadel has played an active role in market structure issues and has advocated for financial legislation.\n\nIn 1999, Congress repealed a provision in the [[Glass Steagall Act|Glass-Steagall Act]] of 1933 that strictly separated banking and trading activities by financial firms. Griffin called dismantling that law \"one of the biggest fiascos of all time\".<ref name=\"RiskNet2012August1\">{{cite news|title=Risk 25 firms of the future: Citadel|url=https://www.citadel.com/_files/uploads/2013/08/risk25citadel.pdf|accessdate=13 July 2015|agency=Infopro Digital Risk (IP) Limited|publisher=Risk.net|date=1 August 2012|location=United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis, Griffin and Citadel called for greater transparency in derivatives trading, a stance at odds with many other hedge funds and major financial firms. The company spoke out against Wall Street for lobbying to delay the implementation of the [[Dodd Frank Act|Dodd-Frank Act]].<ref name=\"RiskNet2012August1\" /><ref name = fintimes>{{cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f3e4b150-1a26-11e3-b3da-00144feab7de.html | title = Derivatives trading safer and more efficient, says Citadel | newspaper = Financial Times | author1 = Michael Mackenzie |author2 = Tom Braithwaite | date = September 10, 2013 | accessdate = July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGriffin has also called for breaking up \"too big to fail\" banks and separating their banking and trading activities.<ref name = fintimes/>\n\nFollowing the 2014 publication of ''Flash Boys'' by [[Michael Lewis]], who claimed financial markets are ''rigged'' \u201dby large, high-speed traders\" (also known as ''high-frequency traders'') Griffin who was not interviewed by Lewis shared his views on the matter during his second congressional hearing.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\">{{cite news|last1=Merrion|first1=Paul|title=Ban high-speed trading? 'Absolutely not,' says Citadel's Griffin|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20140708/NEWS02/140709854/citadel-ceo-griffin-testifies-on-capitol-hill-on-high-frequency-trading|accessdate=7 July 2015|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|issue=Government|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=8 July 2014|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> Griffin said in front of the Senate Banking Committee that from his perspective \u201cthe U.S. equity markets are the fairest, most transparent, resilient and competitive markets in the world.\u201d<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\" /> Griffin expanded by saying that high-frequency trading functions to reconcile discrepancies between options tied to groups of stocks and the stocks themselves: \u201cSomebody has to keep the New York markets in line with the markets in Chicago,\u201d he said. \u201cIt all happens at an extremely low cost in the context of our capital markets.\u201d<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\" />\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\nCitadel leads a business plan competition for the [[National foundation for teaching entrepreneurship|National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship]], mentoring low income high school students.\n\n=== Events ===\nIn 2014 former president Bill Clinton was paid $250,000 by Citadel to speak at New York restaurant Daniel to investors and employees in celebration of the Citadel's founders' 46th birthday.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*''[[The Quants|The Quants: How a New Breed of Math Whizzes Conquered Wall Street and Nearly Destroyed It]]''\n* ''[[Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith Inc. v. Manning]]'', a 2016 Supreme Court case involving [[naked short selling]] claims against Citadel Derivative Group and Merrill Lynch, and others.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.citadelgroup.com Citadel LLC home page]\n* [http://www.chicagoarchitecture.info/Building/1098/Citadel_Center.php Pictures of Citadel Center in Chicago]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070317174334/http://accenture.tekgroup.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=4253 Data management agreement between Citadel and Accenture]\n\n{{Hedge funds}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Hedge funds]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Hedge fund firms in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Investment management companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{UDP|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name           = Citadel LLC\n| logo           = Citadel LLC Logo.svg\n| logo_size      = 220px\n| logo_alt       = \n| type           = [[Limited Liability Company|LLC]]\n| industry       = [[Hedge fund]]\n| founded        = {{Start date and age|1990}} in [[Chicago, Illinois]], US<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2017February3MarekLynne\">{{cite news|last1=Marek|first1=Lynne|title=If one Citadel is good, could two be better?|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20170203/NEWS01/170209978/chicago-billionaire-ken-griffin-splits-citadel-into-two-companies|accessdate=13 December 2019|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|issue=Finance & Banking|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=3 February 2017|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref>\n| predecessor = {{unbulleted list|\u2022 1994-?: Citadel Investment Group, LLC|\u2022 1990<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2017February3MarekLynne\" />-1994: Wellington Financial}}\n| founder        = [[Kenneth C. Griffin]]<br/><small> (Founder & CEO)</small>\n| location = [[Citadel Center]]<br />[[Chicago, Illinois]], US\n| key_people = [[Peng Zhao (businessman)|Peng Zhao]]<br/><small> (CEO of Citadel Securities)</small>\n| num_employees = 1,400\n| products = {{unbulleted list|[[Alternative investments]]| [[Market maker|Market making]]}}\n| revenue = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.citadel.com/}}\n| aum = [[US$]]32 billion<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2019August1FletcherLaurence\">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Laurence|title=Citadel adds traders to profit from central bank stimulus shifts|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1c5272d4-b446-11e9-8cb2-799a3a8cf37b|accessdate=13 December 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=1 August 2019|location=London|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0884-6782}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Citadel LLC''' (formerly known as '''Citadel Investment Group, LLC''') is an American global financial institution. Founded in 1990 by [[Kenneth C. Griffin]], the company operates two primary businesses: Citadel, one of the world's largest alternative asset managers with more than [[US$]]32 billion in assets under management; and Citadel Securities, one of the leading [[market maker]]s in the world, whose trading products include [[Stock|equities]], [[Option (finance)|equity options]], and interest rate swaps for retail and institutional clients.\n\nThe company has more than 1,400 employees, with headquarters in [[Chicago]], and offices throughout [[North America]], [[Asia]] and [[Europe]].\n\n== History ==\nKen Griffin started his trading career out of his dorm room at [[Harvard University]] in 1987 trading convertible-bonds.<ref name=\"WSJ2008November7StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|last2=Zuckerman|first2=Gregory|title=Hedge Fund Selling Puts New Stress on Market|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122602205734807307|accessdate=11 March 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=7 November 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> As a sophomore, he traded convertible bonds and hooked a satellite dish to the roof of his dormitory.<ref name=\"ChicagoMagazine2011June8MeyerGraham\">{{cite news|last1=Meyer|first1=Graham|title=The File on Citadel\u2019s Ken Griffin|url=https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/June-2011/The-File-on-Citadels-Ken-Griffin/|accessdate=11 March 2015|agency=Chicago Tribune Media|issue=Politics & City Life|publisher=Chicago Magazine|date=8 June 2011|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|issn=0362-4595}}</ref> After graduating with a degree in economics, Griffin joined Chicago-based hedge fund Glenwood Partners. According to a ''New York Times'' report, Citadel was started with $4.6 million in capital.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|last2=Craig|first2=Susanne|title=Citadel Chief Gives Up Dream for Investment Bank|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/08/11/citadel-chief-gives-up-dream-for-investment-bank/|accessdate=25 February 2015|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=11 August 2011|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> Citadel was originally named Wellington Financial Group after its flagship fund. The company name was changed to Citadel in 1994. Within eight years, the firm had more than $2 billion in assets.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\">{{cite news|last1=Lux|first1=Hal|title=Boy Wonder|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b15134ls4fblx7/boy-wonder|accessdate=24 July 2015|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=31 August 2001|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=0020-3580}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Citadel started requiring investors to accept terms that \"significantly restrict[ed] their ability to withdraw their capital\", according to ''Institutional Investor''.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\" /> When fund Long-Term Capital Management collapsed later that year, Citadel's capital lockdown made it \"a rare buyer, as desperate hedge funds unloaded bond inventory\".<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2001August31LuxHal\" /> In 2006, Citadel and [[JP Morgan Chase]] took over the energy portfolio and division of failed hedge fund [[Amaranth Advisors]], which had suffered a 65% ($6 billion) loss in assets.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006November26\" /> On November 2006 Citadel issued $2 billion of investment grade bonds to enable access to borrow money at a lower rate than it would otherwise be able to.<ref name=\"WSJ2006November30CoxRob\">{{cite news|last1=Cox|first1=Rob|last2=Christy|first2=John|title=Hedge Fund Citadel Finds a Way To Keep Financial Independence|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116485503536736551|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=BreakingViews|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=30 November 2006|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n[[File:The Citadel Center, Chicago Loop, Chicago, Illinois (11004378483).jpg|thumb|The entrance to Citadel's Chicago headquarters, 2009.]]\nIn October 2008, S&P lowered the outlook for Citadel's Kensington and Wellington Funds from 'stable' to 'negative', citing a 'heightened risk of significant redemptions, challenging performance prospects due to highly volatile capital markets and a very difficult funding environment'.<ref name=\"MarketWatch2008November18BarrAlistair\">{{cite news|last1=Barr|first1=Alistair|title=S&P downgrades debt of Citadel's main fund|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/sp-downgrades-debt-of-citadels-main-fund-after-losses|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Hedge Funds|publisher=MarketWatch|date=18 November 2008|location=San Francisco, United States|language=English}}</ref> In October 2006 following ongoing market concerns over the performance and liquidity of Citadel and the widening of Citadel credit default swaps from 12% upfront on Sep 30, 2008 to 30% upfront on Oct 23, 2008 Citadel held a conference call on Oct 24th 2008 with its noteholders stating that performance to date was -35% for Kensington and Wellington and that the fund maintained a liquid cash position in excess of 30% of capital and had undrawn capacity of $8bn in its tri-party credit lines.<ref name=\"WSJ2018October25StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|last2=Hilsenrath|first2=Jon|title=Citadel Seeks to Reassure Debt Holders|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122488910091368491|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=25 October 2018|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Based on the 2006 SEC filing at the time of its bond offering, the company's leverage ratio was in excess of 7.8 to 1, although some reports suggest this has been reduced to 4 to 1 presently.  This implies a ratio of at least 7.5% of cash to assets.\n\nIn November and again in December 2008 Standard & Poor's Ratings Services lowered its long-term and short-term counterparty credit ratings on Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd. and Citadel Wellington LLC \"to just a notch above junk and then withdrew the ratings at the company's request.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2008December18MillerJay\">{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Jay|title=S&P Cuts, Pulls Counterparty Ratings|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122964818306320429|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=18 December 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In March of 2008, prior to the collapse of Bear Sterns, Citadel was named as a potential bidder for the business. However, Kate Kelly, a Wall Street Journal writer, claims the parties never met to discuss a potential acquisition by Citadel as senior Bear employees believed that Citadel was shorting the company <ref> Kate Kelly, 'Street Fighters: the last 72 hours of Bear Sterns, the Toughest Firm on Wall Street' (London, Penguin Books, 2010) 96 </ref> In February 2009 under pressure from banks Citadel Investment Group sold \"some securities and reduce its borrowing to finance trades.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2009February17PulliamSusan\">{{cite news|last1=Pulliam|first1=Susan|last2=Strasburg|first2=Jenny|title=Brokerages Tighten Hedge Fund Financing|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123483417670296081|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=17 February 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In 2015 the Wall Street Journal described Citadel's position in 2008 as existing \"at the brink of collapse during the financial crisis, amid heavy losses and a struggle to build an investment bank.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" /> During the 2008 financial crisis, the firm's Kensington and Wellington Funds lost 55 percent of their value by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-05-17/citadel-said-to-make-withdrawals-easier-for-hedge-fund-clients | title=Citadel Said to Ease Withdrawal Rules for Hedge-Fund Clients | publisher=Bloomberg | date=17 May 2011 | accessdate=24 July 2015 | author=Burton, Katherine}}</ref> Griffin said, \"we were losing hundreds of millions of dollars a week, if not more,\" and further said \"CNBC parked a van in front of Citadel waiting to break the story of our demise. \u2026 We sold assets. We closed business lines. We let people go. We suspended redemptions. Our management team absorbed $500 million in costs on behalf of our investors...\"<ref name=\"ChicagoTribune2013May22HarrisMelissa\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Melissa|title=Citadel's Kenneth Griffin exposes 'cronyism,' causes a stir at Economic Club|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2013-05-22-ct-biz-0522-confidential-griffin-20130522-story.html|accessdate=24 July 2015|agency=Tribune Publishing Company|issue=Business|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=22 May 2013|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=2165-171X}}</ref>\n\nCitadel suspended shareholder redemptions, which Griffin called one of the \"most difficult decisions\" in Citadel history.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|title=Citadel Clears Its High Water Mark|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/01/20/citadel-clears-its-high-water-mark/|accessdate=13 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=20 January 2012|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> Griffin later conceded that the firm was \"overly confident\" it could \"weather any financial storm\". He covered all investor management expenses during that period.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Citadel\u2019s primary sources of revenue come from charging clients performance fees on their two largest funds: Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\">{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Gregory|last2=Checkler|first2=Joseph|title=Citadel Opens Its 'Gates' on Better Results|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125684219883316671|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=EUROPE|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=30 October 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Because the assets in those funds decreased by 50 percent, Citadel was unable to charge performance fees until it could make up the 50 percent lost; the company would have to make a 100 percent investment return before it could see any more revenue and begin charging clients again.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\">{{cite news|last1=Marek|first1=Lynne|title=Citadel gets slow start in i-banking|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20101106/ISSUE01/311069967/citadel-gets-slow-start-in-i-banking|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=6 November 2010|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> To resolve this issue, Griffin announced that Citadel would incorporate greater portfolio diversification and take up investment strategies that were easier to get out of quickly and also continue efforts to diversify beyond hedge funds, with computer-driven, high-frequency trading.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" /> In 2009, Griffin expanded the scope of business lines at Citadel Securities, a market maker firm founded in 2001, to establish [[investment banking]] and associated financial security sales and trading capabilities.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /><ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" />\n\nOn January 17, 2012, Citadel's flagship funds, Citadel Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC, crossed their respective high water marks, earning back the 50 percent of assets lost during the 2008 financial crisis.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Having made up the losses, Citadel could once again charge client fees for managing their money and take a percentage of profits.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012January20AhmedAzam\" /> Citadel under Griffin's leadership was reported as differentiating from hedge funds rivals post 2008 financial crisis with an \"aggressive expansion.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" /> Starting at the beginning of 2014, over an 18 months period the hedge fund's assets under management increased $10 billion; from $16 billion to $26 billion as a result of \"a 29% rise for its main hedge funds and a flow of new cash.\"<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\">{{cite news|last1=Copeland|first1=Rob|title=Citadel's Ken Griffin Leaves 2008 Tumble Far Behind|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/citadels-ken-griffin-leaves-2008-tumble-far-behind-1438655887|accessdate=23 October 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=3 August 2015|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In January 2020, Citadel Securities paid $97m in China trading settlement, after Chinese regulator ends longstanding investigation into Citadel and other local groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.financemagnates.com/institutional-forex/regulation/citadel-securities-fined-97m-in-china-for-malicious-short-selling/|title=Citadel Securities Pays $97m to Settle with China Regulators}}</ref>\n\n== Citadel & group of companies ==\nThere are three companies Citadel the asset manager, Citadel Securities a market maker and Citadel Technology. \n\n=== Citadel ===\nAs of January 2016, Citadel manages more than $29 billion in capital and is one of the world's largest asset managers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://upstart.bizjournals.com/executives/features/2007/04/16/opening-up-the-citadel.html?page=all | title=Opening Up the Citadel | publisher=Upstart Business Journal | date=16 April 2007 | accessdate=24 February 2015 | author=Kolhatkar, Sheelah}}</ref> Citadel ranks as the eleventh largest hedge fund manager in the world,<ref name=\"Rose-Smith, Imogen 2006 p. 3\">Rose-Smith, Imogen (2006 2006). \"Land of the Giants\" (PDF). Alpha magazine. p. 3. Retrieved 2008-03-20 (dead link).</ref> and in 2006 the second largest multi-strategy hedge fund globally.<ref name=\"fnFinancialNews2006December4HutchingsWilliam\">{{cite news|last1=Hutchings|first1=William|title=Citadel leads the way in financial self-sufficiency|url=https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/citadel-leads-the-way-in-financial-self-sufficiency-20061204|accessdate=27 January 2007|agency=FINANCIAL NEWS|publisher=fn Financial News|date=4 December 2006|language=English}}</ref> Citadel's group of hedge funds rank among the largest and most successful hedge funds in the world.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2014/07/15/two-new-members-elected-university-chicago-board-trustees | title=Two new members elected to University of Chicago Board of Trustees | publisher=U Chicago News | date=15 July 2014 | accessdate=24 February 2015 | author1=Allen, Susie|author2 = Huang, Wen}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Citadel became the first foreign hedge fund to complete a yuan fundraising as part of a program to allow Chinese investors to invest in overseas hedge funds.<ref name=\"barrons\">{{cite news|url=http://online.barrons.com/articles/SB51367578116875004693704580480163105061670|title=Exclusive: Who Makes Money on Your Stock Trades|author=Bill Alpert|date=February 28, 2015|newspaper=Barron's|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Investment strategies ====\nCitadel manages funds across five different investment strategies including equities, commodities, fixed income, quantitative strategies, and credit.<ref name = dealbooknytimes>{{Cite web | url = https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/01/10/citadel-posted-25-return-last-year-beating-industry-again/?_r=1 | title = Citadel Posted 25% Return Last Year, Beating Industry Again | publisher = DealBook | date = January 10, 2013 | accessdate = July 27, 2015 | author = Michael J. De La Merced}}</ref>\n\n'''Commodities''' - Energy trading: Griffin began recruiting the energy traders from Enron the day after it collapsed for a new business including \"a team of traders, meteorologists and researchers\" building what in 2011 was amongst the industries biggest energy trading groups<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\" />\n\n'''Reinsurance''' - Citadel wanted to allocate the investment capital with its two funds, Kensington Global Strategies Fund Ltd and Citadel Wellington LLC, to investments that the company thought to be uncorrelated to their other investment strategies.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\">{{cite news|last1=Zuill|first1=Lilla|last2=Orr|first2=Bernard|title=Hedge fund Citadel shuttering Bermuda reinsurer|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-citadel-reinsurer/exclusive-hedge-fund-citadel-shuttering-bermuda-reinsurer-idUSTRE4A70G420081108|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=7 November 2008|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref> To achieve this move, Citadel, through capitalization via their funds, entered the reinsurer industry, which provides insurance companies with their own policies to spread the risk of losses that they have given to their customers, in 2004 by founding CIG Reinsurance Ltd (CIG Re), a Bermuda-based catastrophe reinsurer providing $450 million in capital.<ref name=\"WSJ2005July27AnandShefali\">{{cite news|last1=Anand|first1=Shefali|title=Looking Afield, Hedge Funds Launch Reinsurance Firms|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112242824590496964|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=27 July 2005|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Citadel additionally founded $500 million reinsurer New Castle Re in 2005, seeking to capitalize on rising prices for reinsurance in the wake of [[Hurricane Katrina|Hurricane Katrina\u2019s]] damage to property coverage costs.<ref name=\"MarketWatch2005November4BarrAlistair\">{{cite news|last1=Barr|first1=Alistair|title=Citadel forms new reinsurer - New Castle Re targets catastrophe reinsurance, AM Best says|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/citadel-forms-new-reinsurer-new-castle-re-am-best-says|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=MarketWatch|date=4 November 2005|location=San Francisco, United States|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006August18AndersonaugJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Andersonaug|first1=Jenny|title=Hedge Funds Place Big Bets on Hurricane Season|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/18/business/18insider.html|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business Day - Insider|page=C7|publisher=New York Times|date=18 August 2006|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> In 2006, Citadel\u2019s two funds had approximately 10 percent of its assets invested in reinsurance.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2006December8PittmanMark\">{{cite news|last1=Pittman|first1=Mark|title=Citadel sells bonds|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20061208/BUSINESS/312089909|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Bloomberg|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=8 December 2006|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\nCitadel wound down CIG Re in November of 2008 because the company could not achieve a financial strength rating, and as a result could not compete in comparison to other companies in the industry.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> Meanwhile, New Castle Re remained open and received an 'A-' rating from [[AM Best]] in November of 2008.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November7ZuillLilla\" /> However, a month later on December 17, 2008, AM Best announced that New Castle Re\u2019s rating was under review when Citadel\u2019s funds experienced increased redemption requests as a result of the financial crisis.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2008December17KentJonathan\">{{cite news|last1=Kent|first1=Jonathan|title=Citadel's hedge fund woes threaten New Castle Re's rating|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20081217/BUSINESS/312179954|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=17 December 2008|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref> Two days later on December 19, it was reported that Citadel would not be renewing the rights in New Castle Re contracts, but that Torus Insurance Holdings in Bermuda would do so.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2008December19\">{{cite news|title=Torus takes New Castle Re renewal rights|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20081219/BUSINESS/312199894|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=19 December 2008|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref> In January of 2009, Citadel placed New Castle Re into run-off.<ref name=\"TheRoyalGazette2009July15\">{{cite news|title=Chris McKeown, the founder of Bermuda reinsurers CIG Reinsurance Ltd. and New Castle Reinsurance Co., has been named chief executive officer of global analytical and specialty practices.|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20090715/BUSINESS/307159960|accessdate=15 December 2019|agency=The Bermuda Press (Holdings) Ltd.|issue=Business|publisher=The Royal Gazette|date=15 July 2009|location=Bermuda|language=English}}</ref>\n\n'''Risk management - '''The firm's risk management philosophy is focused on three main areas: risk capital allocation, stress exposure and liquidity management.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\">{{citeweb|title=Are You Prepared for the Next Crash?|author=Amanda Cantrell|publisher=Institutional Investor's Alpha|date=10 December 2015|url=http://www.institutionalinvestorsalpha.com/Article/3513063/Are-Hedge-Funds-Prepared-for-the-Next-Crash.html}}</ref> Citadel's risk management center has 36 monitors displaying more than 50,000 instruments being traded within the firm's portfolios.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\"/> The firm runs 500 stress tests each day to simulate the impact of potential economic and geopolitical crises or other market dislocation.<ref name=\"Amanda Cantrell\"/> Citadel aggregates investment positions on trading screens to calculate \"more than 500 doomsday scenarios\" to assess the potential of risk for the firm.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\nIn 2014, Citadel rated an A grade for risk management in the annual Institutional Investor Hedge Fund Report Card.<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2014June27HurstGeorgina\">{{cite news|last1=Hurst|first1=Georgina|title=A Winning Night for Hedge Fund Managers and Investors|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b14zbj8sby92mq/a-winning-night-for-hedge-fund-managers-and-investors|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|issue=Corner Office|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=27 June 2014|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=0020-3580}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2015, [[Ben S. Bernanke]], who was the United States [[Federal Reserve]] chairman for eight years, joined Citadel as a senior adviser on global economic and financial issues.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015April16SorkinAndrewRoss\">{{cite news|last1=Sorkin|first1=AndrewRoss|last2=Stevenson|first2=Alexandra|title=Ben Bernanke Will Work With Citadel, a Hedge Fund, as an Adviser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/16/business/ben-bernanke-will-work-with-citadel-a-hedge-fund-as-an-adviser.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|page=B1|publisher=New York Times|date=16 April 2015|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> In January 2017, Joanna Welsh became the Chief Risk Officer.\n\n=== Citadel Securities ===\n==== Market Maker ====\nCitadel Securities was formed in 2001, and is a market maker, providing liquidity and trade execution to retail and institutional clients.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2010November6MarekLynne\" /> Citadel Securities automation has resulted in more reliable trading at lower costs and with tighter spreads.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2012October13MarekLynne\">{{cite news|last1=Marek|first1=Lynne|title=Citadel's big move into the markets|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20121013/ISSUE01/310139980/citadel-becomes-top-broker-on-nasdaq|accessdate=11 December 2014|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=13 October 2012|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> Barron's recently ranked Citadel Securities #1 in providing price improvement for investors in both S&P 500 and non-S&P shares.<ref name = barrons/>\n\nIn 2009 Citadel Investment Group and the Chicago Mercantile Exchanged partnered to create a credit-default swaps electronic-trading platform.<ref name=\"WSJ2009May14LynchSarah\">{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=Sarah|last2=Ng|first2=Serena|title=U.S. Moves to Regulate Derivatives Trade|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124224226775916215|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=14 May 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nCitadel Securities is the largest market maker in options in the U.S., executing about 25 percent U.S.-listed equity options volume.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Citadel wants to shape the rules of the game|author=Lynne Marek|magazine=Crain's Chicago Business|date=5 December 2015|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20151205/ISSUE01/312059991/citadel-wants-to-shape-the-rules-of-the-game}}</ref> According to the ''Wall Street Journal'', about one-third of stock orders from individual investors is completed through Citadel, which accounts for about 10% of the firm's revenue.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\nCitadel Securities also executes about 13 percent of U.S. consolidated volume in equities and 28 percent of U.S. retail equities volume.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-04-11/citadel-fund-said-to-quadruple-with-high-frequency-trades.html | title=Citadel Fund Said to Quadruple With High-Frequency Trades | publisher=Bloomberg Business | date=10 April 2014 | accessdate=26 February 2015 | author=Burton, Katherine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Citadel Securities expanded its market-making offering to interest-rate swaps, one of the most commonly-traded derivatives.<ref name=\"WSJ2014June6AlbaneseChiara\">{{cite news|last1=Albanese|first1=Chiara|title=Citadel to Offer Trading in Interest-Rate Swaps|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/citadel-to-offer-trading-in-interest-rate-swaps-1402070439|accessdate=27 July 2015|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=6 June 2014|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> \n\nBy 2015 Citadel Securities had become the world\u2019s largest interest-rate-swap trader by number of transactions replacing Wall Street banks.<ref name=\"WSJ2015December2ZuckermanGregory\">{{cite news|last1=Zuckerman|first1=Gregory|last2=Cherney|first2=Mike|title=Wall Street Goes Short on Bond Traders|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-goes-short-on-bond-traders-1449102232|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=MARKETS|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=2 December 2015|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n==== Investment bank ====\nIn 2008 Citadel Securities hired 70 people and Rohit D'Souza, a banker from Merrill Lynch, who left after eight months \"to build an investment bank\" and brokerage.<ref name=\"WSJ2009October30ZuckermanGregory\" /> By August 2011, Citadel ended its foray into investment banking to instead focus on electronic trading and market making.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/974e99a6-c465-11e0-ad9a-00144feabdc0|title=Citadel abandons plan to rival banks|last=McCrum|first=Dan|date=August 11, 2011|work=Financial Times|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Citadel Technology ===\nCitadel Technology, established in 2009, is the wholly owned and independently operated affiliate of Citadel.<ref name = wallstreettech>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.wallstreetandtech.com/asset-management/redi-and-citadel-technology-tackle-the--holy-grail-/d/d-id/1268435? | title=REDI and Citadel Technology Tackle the \"Holy Grail\" | magazine=InformationWeek | date=25 September 2013 | accessdate=26 February 2015 | author=Schmerken, Ivy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://marketsmedia.com/citadel-carves-out-technology-niche/ | title=Citadel Carves Out Technology Niche | publisher=Markets Media | date=20 April 2013 | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref> It offers investment management technology, developed internally at Citadel, to a wide range of firms and funds.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.waterstechnology.com/buy-side-technology/analysis/2255916/citadel-technology-preps-endtoend-solutions-suite | title=Citadel technology preps end to end solutions suite | publisher=Waters Technology | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Citadel Technology announced a partnership with [[REDI Global Technologies|REDI]]. The partnership combines Citadel's order management system (OMS) with REDI's execution management capabilities (EMS).<ref name = wallstreettech/>\n\n=== Sold and closed companies ===\nCitadel Solutions - Citadel's fund-administration arm.<ref name=\"WSJ2009March6StrasburgJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Strasburg|first1=Jenny|title=Lower Fees on Citadel's New Fund|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123630573986048063|accessdate=17 December 2019|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=6 March 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n\n=== Citadel Ownership ===\n\nIn November 2006, Citadel became the second [[hedge fund]] to publicly issue debt [[bond (finance)|bonds]] to investors in the form of senior unsecured debt totaling $2 billion, in an arrangement managed by [[Lehman Brothers]] and [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2006November26\">{{cite news|title=Citadel Planning $2 Billion Debt Offering|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2006/11/28/citadel-to-plan-2-billion-debt-offering/|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=26 November 2006|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref>\n\n=== Employees ===\nThe fund has become known for having one of the largest personnel turnovers in Chicago gaining the nickname of \"Chicago's revolving door\"<ref name=\"Fortune2007April3VickersMarcia\">{{cite news|last1=Vickers|first1=Marcia|title=A hedge fund superstar - Citadel founder Ken Griffin is already one of the world's most powerful investors.|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/04/16/8404298/index.htm|accessdate=26 April 2008|agency=Fortune Media IP Limited|publisher=Fortune|date=3 April 2007|location=United States|language=English}}</ref> and the New York Times reported \"the firm is unique in its reputation for being a revolving door.\"<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011August11AhmedAzam\" /><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010December27AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|title=Citadel Founder Offers Thanks and Apologies on Anniversary|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/27/citadel-founder-offers-thanks-apology-on-anniversary|accessdate=14 December 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=27 December 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1553-8095}}</ref> It is also reported that turnover is aligned with the hedge fund industry.<ref name=\"Fortune2007April3VickersMarcia\" />\n\nIn March 2015, Citadel received a Top 10 Great Workplaces in Financial Services ranking by the Great Places to Work Institute, based on a survey by Citadel employees.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2015March6KaposShia\">{{cite news|last1=Kapos|first1=Shia|title=Why Ken Griffin hated one of his first jobs|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20150306/ISSUE09/150309873/ceo-ken-griffin-discusses-citadel-being-honored-as-a-great-place-to-work|accessdate=29 April 2015|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=6 March 2015|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref>\n\n=== Market advocacy ===\nCitadel has played an active role in market structure issues and has advocated for financial legislation.\n\nIn 1999, Congress repealed a provision in the [[Glass Steagall Act|Glass-Steagall Act]] of 1933 that strictly separated banking and trading activities by financial firms. Griffin called dismantling that law \"one of the biggest fiascos of all time\".<ref name=\"RiskNet2012August1\">{{cite news|title=Risk 25 firms of the future: Citadel|url=https://www.citadel.com/_files/uploads/2013/08/risk25citadel.pdf|accessdate=13 July 2015|agency=Infopro Digital Risk (IP) Limited|publisher=Risk.net|date=1 August 2012|location=United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis, Griffin and Citadel called for greater transparency in derivatives trading, a stance at odds with many other hedge funds and major financial firms. The company spoke out against Wall Street for lobbying to delay the implementation of the [[Dodd Frank Act|Dodd-Frank Act]].<ref name=\"RiskNet2012August1\" /><ref name = fintimes>{{cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f3e4b150-1a26-11e3-b3da-00144feab7de.html | title = Derivatives trading safer and more efficient, says Citadel | newspaper = Financial Times | author1 = Michael Mackenzie |author2 = Tom Braithwaite | date = September 10, 2013 | accessdate = July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGriffin has also called for breaking up \"too big to fail\" banks and separating their banking and trading activities.<ref name = fintimes/>\n\nFollowing the 2014 publication of ''Flash Boys'' by [[Michael Lewis]], who claimed financial markets are ''rigged'' \u201dby large, high-speed traders\" (also known as ''high-frequency traders'') Griffin who was not interviewed by Lewis shared his views on the matter during his second congressional hearing.<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\">{{cite news|last1=Merrion|first1=Paul|title=Ban high-speed trading? 'Absolutely not,' says Citadel's Griffin|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20140708/NEWS02/140709854/citadel-ceo-griffin-testifies-on-capitol-hill-on-high-frequency-trading|accessdate=7 July 2015|agency=Crain Communications, Inc.|issue=Government|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=8 July 2014|location=Chicago, IL, United States|language=English|url-access=limited|issn=1557-7902}}</ref> Griffin said in front of the Senate Banking Committee that from his perspective \u201cthe U.S. equity markets are the fairest, most transparent, resilient and competitive markets in the world.\u201d<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\" /> Griffin expanded by saying that high-frequency trading functions to reconcile discrepancies between options tied to groups of stocks and the stocks themselves: \u201cSomebody has to keep the New York markets in line with the markets in Chicago,\u201d he said. \u201cIt all happens at an extremely low cost in the context of our capital markets.\u201d<ref name=\"CrainsChicagoBusiness2014July8MerrionPaul\" />\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\nCitadel leads a business plan competition for the [[National foundation for teaching entrepreneurship|National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship]], mentoring low income high school students.\n\n=== Events ===\nIn 2014 former president Bill Clinton was paid $250,000 by Citadel to speak at New York restaurant Daniel to investors and employees in celebration of the Citadel's founders' 46th birthday.<ref name=\"WSJ2015August3CopelandRob\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*''[[The Quants|The Quants: How a New Breed of Math Whizzes Conquered Wall Street and Nearly Destroyed It]]''\n* ''[[Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith Inc. v. Manning]]'', a 2016 Supreme Court case involving [[naked short selling]] claims against Citadel Derivative Group and Merrill Lynch, and others.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.citadelgroup.com Citadel LLC home page]\n* [http://www.chicagoarchitecture.info/Building/1098/Citadel_Center.php Pictures of Citadel Center in Chicago]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070317174334/http://accenture.tekgroup.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=4253 Data management agreement between Citadel and Accenture]\n\n{{Hedge funds}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Hedge funds]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Hedge fund firms in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Investment management companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "DonSpencer1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Slight reformatting and citation in body", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citadel_LLC"}
{"title_page": "2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 2019\n| team=New Hampshire Wildcats\n| image= UNH Wildcats.png\n| image_size= 150\n| conference= Colonial Athletic Association\n| division= \n| short_conf= CAA\n| STATSRank = \n| FCSCoachRank = \n| record = 6\u20135\n| conf_record = 5\u20133\n| head_coach= [[Ricky Santos]] (interim)\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_coach=\n| oc_year = \n| def_coach=[[John Lyons (American football)|John Lyons]]\n| dc_year = 8th\n| off_scheme= \n| def_scheme=\n| stadium= [[Wildcat Stadium (University of New Hampshire)|Wildcat Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 11,015)\n| champion = \n| bowl= \n| bowl_result = \n}}\n{{2019 CAA football standings}}\nThe '''2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team''' represented the [[University of New Hampshire]] in the [[2019 NCAA Division I FCS football season]]. They were led by interim head coach [[Ricky Santos]], due to longtime head coach [[Sean McDonnell]] taking a leave of absence for medical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/08/27/new-hampshire-football-coach-sean-mcdonnell-on-leave-for-health-reasons/ |title=New Hampshire football coach Sean McDonnell on leave for health reasons |first=John |last=Connolly |website=[[Boston Herald]] |url-access=limited |date=August 27, 2019 |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref> The team played their home games at [[Wildcat Stadium (University of New Hampshire)|Wildcat Stadium]] and were a member of the [[Colonial Athletic Association]] (CAA). The Wildcats finished the season 6\u20135, 5\u20133 in CAA play to finish tied for third place.\n\n==Previous season==\n{{main|2018 New Hampshire Wildcats football team}}\nThe Wildcats finished the [[2018 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2018 season]] 4\u20137, 3\u20135 in CAA play to finish in ninth place.\n\n==Preseason==\n===CAA poll===\nIn the CAA preseason poll released on July 23, 2019, the Wildcats were predicted to finish in seventh place.<ref name=\"caa preseason\">{{cite web|last=Washburn|first=Rob|url=https://caasports.com/news/2019/7/22/james-madison-picked-to-capture-caa-football-championship-in-2019.aspx|title=James Madison Picked to Capture CAA Football Championship in 2019|publisher=Colonial Athletic Association|date=July 23, 2019|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=New Hampshire Wildcats|Predicted finish|Team|Votes (1st place)}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1 || James Madison || 238 (20)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2 || Towson || 217 (3)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 3 || Maine || 201 (1)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 4 || Elon || 164\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 5 || Delaware || 162\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 6 || Stony Brook || 151\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 7 || '''New Hampshire''' || 109\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 8 || Rhode Island || 104\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 9 || Villanova || 84\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 10 || Richmond || 62\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 11 || William & Mary || 58\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 12 || Albany || 34\n|}\n\n===Preseason All\u2013CAA team===\nThe Wildcats had one player selected to the preseason all-CAA team.<ref name=\"caa preseason\"/>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''Defense'''\n\nPop Lacey \u2013 S\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| opprank = y\n| rankyear = 2019\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division I FCS\n| poll = STATS\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 7\n| time = 1:00 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[2019 Holy Cross Crusaders football team|Holy Cross]]\n| site_stadium = [[Fitton Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester, MA]]\n| tv = [[Stadium (sports network)|Stadium]]\n| score = 10\u201313\n| attend = 8,372\n| source = <ref>{{cite web |title=New Hampshire vs. Holy Cross - Game Summary - September 7, 2019 - ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game/_/gameI