{"title_page": "2020 National Camogie League", "text_new": "{{Infobox GAA League\n|league   = 2020 National Camogie League \n|image    =\n|dates    = 1 February \u2013 April, 2020 \n|teams    =  27\n|team1    =  \n|captain1 =  \n|manager1 = \n|titles   = \n|team2    =  \n|captain2 = \n|manager2 =  \n|previous = [[2019 National Camogie League|2019]]\n|next     = [[2021 National Camogie League|2021]]\n|two= \n|three= \n}}\nThe '''2020 [[National Camogie League]]''', known for sponsorship reasons as the '''[[Shop Direct|Littlewoods Ireland]] Camogie Leagues''', takes place in [[Ireland]] in spring 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.munster-express.ie/sports/gaa-hurling/camogie-fixtures-2019/|title=Camogie Fixtures 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tipperarylive.ie/news/sport/508215/forty-nine-players-named-on-the-tipperary-senior-and-intermediate-camogie-panel-ahead-of-league-campaign.html|title=Forty-nine players named on the Tipperary senior and intermediate camogie panel ahead of league campaign|website=www.tipperarylive.ie}}</ref> Several new rules are being trialled, to do with contact, persistent fouling, puckouts, dropping the [[camogie stick]], hand-pass goals and penalty shots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/new-camogie-rules-trial-2020-national-league-421448|title=Badly Needed New Camogie Rules To Be Trialled In 2020 National League|first=P. J.|last=Browne|website=Balls.ie}}</ref>\n\nThe league was originally scheduled to end in April 2020, but public health measures introduced to combat the spread of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] caused the final stages to be delayed, with potential for them to be shortened or cancelled altogether.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clareecho.ie/u21-championship-delayed-clare-cup-deferred/|title=U21 championship delayed with Clare Cup start deferred|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://galwaybayfm.ie/sports/sporting-events-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-scare/|title=Sporting Events Postponed Due to Coronavirus Scare|first=Sport|last=GBFM|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/a-comprehensive-guide-as-irish-and-global-sport-shuts-down-in-effort-to-contain-spread-of-covid-19-39039369.html|title=Coronavirus: A comprehensive guide as Irish and global sport shuts down in effort to contain spread of Covid-19|website=independent}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n===League structure===\nThe 2020 National Camogie League consists of three divisions: 9 in Division 1, 14 in Division 2 and 4 in Division 3; division 1 is divided into two groups and Division 2 is divided into three groups. Each team plays every other team in its group once. 3 points are awarded for a win and 1 for a draw.\n\nIf two teams are level on points, the tie-break is:\n* winners of the head-to-head game are ranked ahead\n* if the head-to-head match was a draw, ranking is determined by the points difference (i.e. total scored minus total conceded in all games)\n* if the points difference is equal, ranking is determined by the total scored\n\nIf three or more teams are level on league points, rankings are determined solely by points difference.\n\n===Finals ===\nThe winners of each group in Division 1 contest the National Camogie League final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearedublin.com/camogie/dublin-seniors-start-the-2020-national-camogie-league-against-galway/|title=Dublin Seniors Start The 2020 National Camogie League Against Galway|first=Nigel|last=McCarthy|date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Division 2, the three group winners and runners-up contest the quarter-finals; the three quarter-final winners then play a semi-final and final.\n\nThe top two teams in Division 3 contest the Division 3 final.\n\n==Fixtures and results==\n\n===Division 1===\n====Group 1====\n\n{| style=border-collapse:collapse border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5\n|- align=center bgcolor=#efefef\n!Team\n!Pld\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!Diff\n!Pts\n!Notes\n\n|- ali